<TD ALIGN="left" BGCOLOR="#ffffff" VALIGN="top"><BLOCKQUOTE><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif" COLOR="#000080" SIZE="+1"><B>Stewart</B></FONT>
 <I>(Stuart)</I> 

<P><FONT SIZE="-1"><I>'Virescit Vulnere Virtus'</I></FONT></P>


<P ALIGN="right"><FONT SIZE="-2"><I>Stewart Hunting Tartan<BR>
&copy;1995-2007 Gazetteer for Scotland</I></FONT></P><IMG ALIGN="right" HSPACE="12" VSPACE="2" HEIGHT="250" WIDTH="250" SRC="/scotgaz/images/P1543.GIF" ALT="Stewart Hunting Tartan">


<DIV ALIGN="justify"><FONT SIZE="-1"><P>Stewart was the Royal House of Scotland between 1371 and 1603 and, following the <i>Union of the Crowns</i>, of Scotland and England between 1603 and 1714. There were fourteen Stewart monarchs in all.<P>The line is decended from Walter, created hereditary Great Steward of Scotland by King David I (1084 - 1153). Another Walter, the 6th Great Steward, distinguished himself at Bannockburn and was knighted by Robert the Bruce. He also supported Paisley Abbey. Walter married Robert's sister, and their son later became King Robert II.<P>A branch of this family form the Stuarts of Bute, who are hereditary Sheriffs of Bute and Arran, Keepers of Rothesay Castle and Marquesses of Bute. The Stuarts of Darnley became the Earls of Lennox. The Stewart Earldoms have included Angus, Arran, Atholl, Bothwell, Buchan, Caithness, Carrick, Fife, Galloway, Mar, March, Menteith, Moray, Okney, Strathearn and Traquair. <P>The family can trace its ancestry back to Brittany (France), and had lands in East Lothian and Renfrewshire.<BR></FONT></DIV>

